{"focus":{"id":"8925c85f-8668-5e82-bbd7-df35f6459542","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9eebe1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.G.B.4","description":"Know the formulas for the area and circumference of a circle and use them to solve problems; give an informal derivation of the relationship between the circumference and area of a circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"G","cluster":"7.G.B","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"2736f26a-1e5c-5b90-be28-5f4c801bfd82","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba030d6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.B.6","description":"Compose simple shapes to form larger shapes. *For example, \"Can you join these two triangles with full sides touching to make a rectangle?\"*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"472fb1eb-7c0d-5904-b9a3-e5a6d94b4ab3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9896-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.1","description":"Describe objects in the environment using names of shapes, and describe the relative positions of these objects using terms such as above, below, beside, in front of, behind, and next to.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"308440b4-e522-5061-85a6-4a5a0a3dce51","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dcb8a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.2","description":"Correctly name shapes regardless of their orientations or overall size.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d4594d7e-edbd-5c0b-a233-35cccdbbcecf","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e8f43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.3","description":"Identify shapes as two-dimensional (lying in a plane, \"flat\") or three-dimensional (\"solid\").","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"96c55133-2681-59f9-93af-d27881cbf101","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dce41-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.2","description":"Directly compare two objects with a measurable attribute in common, to see which object has \"more of\"/\"less of\" the attribute, and describe the difference. *For example, directly compare the heights of two children and describe one child as taller/shorter.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"fb8a2e0d-695f-556f-be81-53427c5011dc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9af3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.1","description":"Describe measurable attributes of objects, such as length or weight. Describe several measurable attributes of a single object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"226b21e4-6dd2-53ce-bd17-68b5c61d3093","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d1dd5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.G.A.2","description":"Compose two-dimensional shapes (rectangles, squares, trapezoids, triangles, half-circles, and quarter-circles) or three-dimensional shapes (cubes, right rectangular prisms, right circular cones, and right circular cylinders) to create a composite shape, and compose new shapes from the composite shape.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"G","cluster":"1.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"5202eb12-da14-59b3-aaca-d84bfb21b73d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d205c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.2","description":"Express the length of an object as a whole number of length units, by laying multiple copies of a shorter object (the length unit) end to end; understand that the length measurement of an object is the number of same-size length units that span it with no gaps or overlaps.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a5c72e23-4039-51b9-8ab3-86f4708d7381","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bd85b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.1","description":"Order three objects by length; compare the lengths of two objects indirectly by using a third object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e7b8f46-92a9-5817-ba90-cf67a66bc81a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9be543-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.A.1","description":"Measure the length of an object by selecting and using appropriate tools such as rulers, yardsticks, meter sticks, and measuring tapes.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"73138360-d2c3-53b0-aa36-91b9ea38f0f8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d290b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.G.A.2","description":"Partition a rectangle into rows and columns of same-size squares and count to find the total number of them.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"G","cluster":"2.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"35ca96cb-de02-567b-99f7-dd938c89fb0d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ec6c0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.4","description":"Determine the unknown whole number in a multiplication or division equation relating three whole numbers. *For example, determine the unknown number that makes the equation true in each of the equations $8 \\times ? = 48$, $5 = \\Box \\div 3$, $6 \\times 6 = ?$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"813f4e23-c302-532a-845f-cb693fe12b35","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1826d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.7.b","description":"Multiply side lengths to find areas of rectangles with whole-number side lengths in the context of solving real world and mathematical problems, and represent whole-number products as rectangular areas in mathematical reasoning.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"b6ea7b48-aac1-55c4-91f8-c5c13ae946d3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0a209-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.D.8","description":"Solve real world and mathematical problems involving perimeters of polygons, including finding the perimeter given the side lengths, finding an unknown side length, and exhibiting rectangles with the same perimeter and different areas or with the same area and different perimeters.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"3dbbcda5-5868-5b18-a07e-5e8b4eb24e58","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba108fe-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.7.a","description":"Find the area of a rectangle with whole-number side lengths by tiling it, and show that the area is the same as would be found by multiplying the side lengths.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"aad309a8-f04d-5e11-b9b4-7bbe36d72205","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f5a86-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.5","description":"Recognize area as an attribute of plane figures and understand concepts of area measurement.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"fc25c5ec-af04-54ae-a25e-8e2be4885082","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fddc7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.6","description":"Measure areas by counting unit squares (square cm, square m, square in, square ft, and improvised units).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"1b9cdeb7-7c76-55d4-ae26-2a843a886722","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e283e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.MD.A.3","description":"Apply the area and perimeter formulas for rectangles in real world and mathematical problems. *For example, find the width of a rectangular room given the area of the flooring and the length, by viewing the area formula as a multiplication equation with an unknown factor.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"MD","cluster":"4.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"509e1786-9a54-570f-8078-d95c85f3d325","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ecdc0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.NF.B.4","description":"Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication to multiply a fraction by a whole number.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"NF","cluster":"4.NF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"bf78dc38-1de7-57d1-a602-2afe9dbbe51a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9edad5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.NF.B.4","description":"Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication to multiply a fraction or whole number by a fraction.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"NF","cluster":"5.NF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"617b9ad8-2ebc-54b6-8ae7-166d7e780c9e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c2393-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.G.A.1","description":"Find the area of right triangles, other triangles, special quadrilaterals, and polygons by composing into rectangles or decomposing into triangles and other shapes; apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"G","cluster":"6.G.A","level":"standard"}],"descendants":[{"id":"8957175b-6ae1-533c-82e1-9059810669cb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f9d82-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.B.5","description":"Derive using similarity the fact that the length of the arc intercepted by an angle is proportional to the radius, and define the radian measure of the angle as the constant of proportionality; derive the formula for the area of a sector.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e097c63-b820-53c3-85ef-03d9da9e0944","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c70b3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.1","description":"Give an informal argument for the formulas for the circumference of a circle, area of a circle, volume of a cylinder, pyramid, and cone.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ef4ff21d-897e-598d-b731-2d5b8a2b31c3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c77f2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.1","description":"Use geometric shapes, their measures, and their properties to describe objects (e.g., modeling a tree trunk or a human torso as a cylinder).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"636789d4-4a59-5e0e-91cd-902823701dd5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e763a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.3","description":"Apply geometric methods to solve design problems (e.g., designing an object or structure to satisfy physical constraints or minimize cost; working with typographic grid systems based on ratios).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"fff120ce-1225-5947-ba41-aa83e8f29989","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c675d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.1","description":"Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"3b8fbea4-86ea-5a73-9ebd-e4a2936baf33","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9da784-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.2","description":"(+) Give an informal argument using Cavalieri's principle for the formulas for the volume of a sphere and other solid figures.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"3f55d232-bf86-54b0-8188-424990f7f7c7","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e70eb-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GMD.A.3","description":"Use volume formulas for cylinders, pyramids, cones, and spheres to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GMD","cluster":"HSG-GMD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"2b599071-8547-5521-add4-18ee082a5d2a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d9f54-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.2","description":"Explain how the unit circle in the coordinate plane enables the extension of trigonometric functions to all real numbers, interpreted as radian measures of angles traversed counterclockwise around the unit circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"088892fa-d4c0-5124-bbda-72204983bd4f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f0c6f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.4","description":"(+) Use the unit circle to explain symmetry (odd and even) and periodicity of trigonometric functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4ace16fc-ec48-547d-8fe8-17bb9011e990","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f9a9b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.5","description":"Choose trigonometric functions to model periodic phenomena with specified amplitude, frequency, and midline.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"d0979cb7-6dd3-5950-9230-4dbf862eb0ee","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba00e93-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.6","description":"(+) Understand that restricting a trigonometric function to a domain on which it is always increasing or always decreasing allows its inverse to be constructed.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"c19d1d86-6056-5558-82a1-e8bc0f04654b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0bf6b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.8","description":"Prove the Pythagorean identity $\\sin^{2}(\\theta) + \\cos^{2}(\\theta) = 1$ and use it to find $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ given $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ and the quadrant of the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"5043f047-9f14-56fb-9c1f-e1d5c28af877","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0ef63-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.9","description":"(+) Prove the addition and subtraction formulas for sine, cosine, and tangent and use them to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"cc2355c0-fe93-597c-ae5d-cee6e823d018","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba070dd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.7","description":"(+) Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate the solutions using technology, and interpret them in terms of the context.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"64faff1c-68b2-5673-b552-23538ed39193","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa8da-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.B.5","description":"(+) Represent addition, subtraction, multiplication, and conjugation of complex numbers geometrically on the complex plane; use properties of this representation for computation. *For example, $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)^{3} = 8$ because $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)$ has modulus 2 and argument $120^{\\circ}$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"b1e4c13f-eddc-544f-9fe8-7